<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">5.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Approval of an amendment to the Company&#146;s Restated Certificate of Incorporation to eliminate the classified Board of Directors to provide for the annual election
of all directors; and </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">6.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Transaction of any other business that may properly come before the meeting or any adjournment thereof. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Holders of record of the Company&#146;s common stock as of the close of business on March&nbsp;18, 2013, are entitled to notice of, and to vote at, the
annual meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">It is important that your shares are represented at the meeting. We encourage you to designate the proxies named on the
enclosed proxy card to vote your shares on your behalf and per your instructions. This action does not limit your right to vote in person or to attend the meeting. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:55%; text-indent:-2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">By order of the Board of Directors </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:55%; text-indent:-2%">

STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">April 3, 2013 </FONT></P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Important Notice Regarding the Availability of Proxy
Materials </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>for the Annual Meeting of Shareholders to be held on May&nbsp;16, 2013: </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>This proxy statement, along with the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the fiscal </B></FONT></P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Throughout this proxy statement, references to the &#147;stock split&#148; relate to the two-for-one stock split of Apache common stock distributed in shares of common

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>APACHE CORPORATION </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>One Post Oak Central </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>2000 Post Oak Boulevard, Suite 100 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Houston, Texas 77056-4400
</B></FONT></P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">April 3, 2013 </FONT></P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>PROXY STATEMENT </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_1"></A>GENERAL </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">This proxy statement contains information about the 2013 annual meeting of shareholders of Apache Corporation. In this proxy statement both
&#147;Apache&#148; and the &#147;Company&#148; refer to Apache Corporation. This proxy statement and the enclosed proxy card are being mailed to you by the Company&#146;s Board of Directors starting on or about April 3, 2013. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_2"></A>Purpose of the Annual Meeting </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">At the Company&#146;s annual meeting, shareholders will vote on the following matters: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Items 1- 3: election of directors; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

to be acted on at the meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_3"></A>Who Can Vote </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Only shareholders of record holding shares of Apache common stock at the close of business on the record date, March&nbsp;18, 2013, are entitled to receive notice of the annual meeting and to vote the
shares of Apache common stock they held on that date. The Company&#146;s stock transfer books will not be closed. A complete list of shareholders entitled to vote at the annual meeting will be available for examination by any Apache shareholder at
2000 Post Oak Boulevard, Suite 100, Houston, Texas 77056-4400, for purposes relating to the annual meeting, during normal business hours for a period of ten days before the meeting. </FONT></P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">As of February&nbsp;28, 2013, there were 391,835,046 shares of Apache common stock issued and outstanding. Holders of Apache common stock are entitled to one vote per share and are not allowed to cumulate
votes in the election of directors. The enclosed proxy card shows the number of shares that you are entitled to vote. </FONT></P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_4">
</A>How to Vote </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">If your shares of Apache common stock are held by a broker, bank or other nominee (in &#147;street name&#148;), you will
receive instructions from them on how to vote your shares. If your shares are held by a broker </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">1 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">
and you do not give the broker specific instructions on how to vote your shares, your broker may vote your shares at its discretion on &#147;routine&#148; matters to be acted upon at the annual
meeting. However, your shares will not be voted on any of the &#147;non-routine&#148; matters described below. An absence of voting instructions on any &#147;non-routine&#148; matters will result in a &#147;broker non-vote.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The only &#147;routine&#148; matter to be acted upon at the annual meeting is Item&nbsp;4 &#151; ratification of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP as the
Company&#146;s independent auditors. All other matters to be acted upon at the annual meeting are &#147;non-routine&#148; matters and, as such, if you hold all or any portion of your shares in street name and you do not give your broker or bank
specific instructions on how to vote your shares, your shares will not be voted on any of the following &#147;non-routine&#148; matters: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

to provide for the annual election of all directors. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">If you hold shares of Apache common stock in your own name (as a
&#147;shareholder of record&#148;), you may give the Company instructions on how your shares are to be voted by: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">marking, signing, dating, and returning the enclosed proxy card in the postage-paid envelope provided. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I></I></B>When using internet or telephone voting, the voting systems will verify that you are a shareholder through the use of a company number for
Apache and a unique control number for you. <B><I>If you vote by internet or telephone, please do not also mail the enclosed proxy card. </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Whichever method you use to transmit your instructions, your shares of Apache common stock will be voted as you direct. If you sign and return the
enclosed proxy card or otherwise designate the proxies named on the proxy card to vote on your behalf, but do not specify how to vote your shares, they will be voted: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">2 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_5"></A>Voting 401(k) Savings Plan Shares </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">If you are an employee or former employee participating in the Apache 401(k) Savings Plan and have shares of Apache common stock credited to your plan
account as of the record date, such shares are shown on the enclosed proxy card, and you have the right to direct the plan trustee regarding how to vote those shares. The trustee for the 401(k) Savings Plan is Fidelity Management Trust Company.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The trustee will vote the shares in your plan account in accordance with your instructions. If you do not send instructions (in the manner
described under &#147;How to Vote&#148; above) or if your proxy card is not received by May&nbsp;13, 2013, the shares credited to your account will be voted by the trustee in the same proportion as it votes shares for which it did receive timely
instructions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_6"></A>Revoking a Proxy </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">You may revoke a proxy before it is voted by submitting a new proxy with a later date (by internet, telephone or mail), by voting at the meeting, or by filing a written revocation with Apache&#146;s
corporate secretary. Your attendance at the annual meeting alone will not automatically revoke your proxy. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_7"></A>Quorum </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The
presence at the annual meeting, in person or by proxy, of the holders of a majority of the shares of Apache common stock outstanding on the record date will constitute a quorum, permitting the business of the meeting to be conducted. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_8"></A>Votes Needed </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I><U>Election of Directors</U></I></B><B></B><B><I>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></B>The affirmative vote of a majority of the votes cast at the annual
meeting is required for the election of directors. You may vote FOR or AGAINST any or all director nominees or you may ABSTAIN as to one or more director nominees. As set forth in our bylaws, only votes FOR or AGAINST the election of a director
nominee will be counted. Abstentions and broker non-votes count for quorum purposes, but not for purposes of the election of directors. A vote to ABSTAIN is not treated as a vote FOR or AGAINST and thus, will have no effect on the outcome of the
vote. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I><U>Ratification of the Appointment of Independent Auditors</U></I></B>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The affirmative vote of a majority
of the votes cast at the annual meeting is required for ratification of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP as the Company&#146;s independent auditors. You may vote FOR or AGAINST the ratification of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP as the Company&#146;s
independent auditors or you may ABSTAIN. Votes cast FOR or AGAINST and ABSTENTIONS with respect to this matter will be counted as shares entitled to vote on the matter. Broker non-votes will be counted as shares entitled to vote on this matter. A
vote to ABSTAIN will have the effect of a vote AGAINST ratification of the appointment of our independent registered public accounting firm. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I><U>Advisory Vote to Approve the Compensation of Named Executive Officers</U></I></B>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;You may vote FOR or AGAINST the
advisory vote to approve the compensation of our named executive officers or you may ABSTAIN. A majority of the shares of the Company&#146;s common stock present in person or represented by proxy at our annual meeting and entitled to vote must be
voted FOR approval of the advisory proposal in order for it to pass. Votes cast FOR or AGAINST and ABSTENTIONS with respect to the proposal will be counted as shares entitled to vote on the proposal. Broker non-votes will not be counted as shares
entitled to vote on the proposal. A vote to ABSTAIN will have the effect of a vote AGAINST the proposal. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">3 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I><U>Approval of an Amendment to the 2011 Omnibus Plan</U></I></B>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A majority of
the shares of the Company&#146;s common stock present in person or represented by proxy at our Annual Meeting and entitled to vote must be voted FOR approval of the amendment to the 2011 Omnibus Plan to increase the number of shares of the
Company&#146;s common stock authorized for issuance under the plan in order for it to pass. Votes cast FOR or AGAINST and ABSENTIONS with respect to the proposal will be counted as shares entitled to vote on the proposal. Broker non-votes will not
be counted as shares entitled to vote on the proposal. A vote to ABSTAIN will have the effect of a vote AGAINST the proposal. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I><U>Approval of an Amendment to our Restated Certificate of Incorporation.</U></I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Four-fifths (80%)&nbsp;of the
outstanding shares of the Company&#146;s common stock must be voted FOR the proposal to amend the Company&#146;s Restated Certificate of Incorporation to eliminate the classified Board of Directors to provide for the annual election of all directors
in order for it to pass. You may vote FOR or AGAINST the proposal, or you may ABSTAIN. Broker non-votes will be counted as shares entitled to vote on this matter. A vote to ABSTAIN or a broker non-vote will have the effect of a vote AGAINST the
proposal. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I><U>Other Business</U>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></B>The affirmative vote of a majority of the votes cast at the annual
meeting is required for approval of any other business which may properly come before the meeting or any adjournment thereof. Only votes FOR or AGAINST approval of any other business will be counted. Abstentions and broker non-votes count for quorum
purposes, but not for the voting on the approval of such other business. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_9"></A>Who Counts the Votes </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Representatives of Wells Fargo Bank, N.A. will tabulate the votes and act as inspectors of the election. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">4 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_10"></A>ELECTION OF DIRECTORS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>(ITEM NOS. 1-3 ON PROXY CARD) </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company&#146;s Restated Certificate of Incorporation provides that, as near as numerically possible, one-third of the directors shall be elected at each annual meeting of shareholders. Unless
directors earlier resign or are removed, their terms are for three years, and continue thereafter until their successors are elected and qualify as directors. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The current terms of directors Eugene C. Fiedorek, Chansoo Joung, and William C. Montgomery will expire at the annual meeting. Each of Messrs. Fiedorek, Joung, and Montgomery have been recommended by the
Company&#146;s Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee and nominated by the Board of Directors for election by the shareholders to an additional three-year term. If elected, Messrs. Fiedorek, Joung, and Montgomery will serve beginning upon
their election until the annual meeting of shareholders in 2016. </FONT></P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Scott&nbsp;D. Josey, who has served as a director since February 2011,
resigned from the Company&#146;s Board of Directors effective March&nbsp;15, 2013, in order to pursue other opportunities in the energy industry. Patricia Albjerg Graham, who has served as a director since 2002, will retire from the Company&#146;s
Board of Directors effective May&nbsp;16, 2013. </FONT></P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Unless otherwise instructed, all proxies will be voted in favor of these nominees. If one
or more of the nominees is unwilling or unable to serve, the proxies will be voted only for the remaining named nominees. Proxies cannot be voted for more than three nominees. The Board of Directors knows of no nominee for director who is unwilling
or unable to serve. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS UNANIMOUSLY RECOMMENDS THAT YOU VOTE &#147;FOR&#148; THE ELECTION OF EACH OF THE DIRECTORS.
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_11"></A>NOMINEES FOR ELECTION AS DIRECTORS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Biographical information, including principal occupation and business experience during the last five years, of each nominee for director, is set forth
below. Unless otherwise stated, the principal occupation of each nominee has been the same for the past five years. In addition, each nominee&#146;s experience, qualifications, attributes or skills to serve on our Board are discussed under the
heading &#147;Qualifications of Directors&#148; below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>EUGENE C. FIEDOREK, </B>81, a private investor, joined the Company&#146;s Board of
Directors in 1988. Formerly, Mr.&nbsp;Fiedorek was co-founder, president and managing director of EnCap Investments L.C., a Dallas, Texas, energy investment banking firm, from 1988 until March 1999, when EnCap was acquired by El Paso Energy. Prior
to founding EnCap, Mr.&nbsp;Fiedorek was the managing director of the Energy Banking Group of First RepublicBank Corp. in Dallas, Texas, from 1978 to 1988. At Apache, he is a member of the Audit Committee. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>CHANSOO JOUNG</B>, 52, joined the Company&#146;s Board of Directors in February 2011. Mr.&nbsp;Joung serves as a senior advisor at Warburg Pincus LLC,
a firm at which he was a partner from 2005 to 2010. Prior to joining Warburg Pincus, Mr.&nbsp;Joung was co-head, then head, of the Americas Natural Resources Group in the investment banking division of Goldman Sachs from 1999 to 2004, and he served
as a corporate finance banker in the Natural Resources Group from 1994 to 1999.&nbsp;While in the Natural Resources Group, he was promoted to managing director in 1996 and partner in 1998.&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Joung founded and led Goldman Sachs&#146;
London-based European Energy Group in investment banking from 1992 to 1994. He </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">5 </FONT></P>

began his career with Goldman Sachs in 1987 in the corporate finance department and also worked in the mergers and acquisitions department until 1990.&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Joung also served as a
director of Targa Resources Corp. and Targa Resources Partners, LP from 2007 to February 2011. At Apache, he is a member of the Audit Committee and a member of the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>WILLIAM C. MONTGOMERY</B>, 51, joined the Company&#146;s Board of Directors in September 2011.&nbsp;Since July 2011, Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery has served as
a managing director of Quantum Energy Partners, a private equity firm that focuses on investments in the energy and power industries, and is a member of Quantum&#146;s executive and investment committees.&nbsp;Prior to joining Quantum,
Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery was a partner in the investment banking division of Goldman, Sachs&nbsp;&amp; Co. from October 2002 to April 2011, where he headed the firm&#146;s Americas Natural Resources Group as well as its Houston office. During his 22
years as an investment banker, Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery focused globally on large cap energy companies primarily in the upstream, integrated, and oil service sectors. At Apache, Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery is a member of the Management Development and
Compensation Committee and a member of the Stock Plan Committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_12"></A>CONTINUING DIRECTORS

cardiovascular surgeon. Dr. Ferlic is the founder of Surgical Services of the Great Plains, P.C. and served as its president from 1974 to 1993. He was an elected Regent of the University of Nebraska from November 2000 until his retirement in January

Executive Committee, and served as lead director from February 2011 until February 2013.</FONT></TD>

The Phoenix Resource Companies, Inc., a public oil and gas company, from 1990 until May 1996, when Phoenix merged with Apache. At Apache, he is chairman of the Management Development and Compensation Committee and a member of the Executive

<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>RODMAN D. PATTON</B>, 69, joined the Company&#146;s Board of Directors in December 1999. Mr.&nbsp;Patton has over 30 years of experience in oil and gas investment banking and
corporate finance activity, including serving as managing director of the Merrill Lynch Energy Group from 1993 until April 1999. Prior to joining Merrill Lynch, he was with The First Boston Corporation (later Credit Suisse First Boston) and Eastman
Dillon, Union Securities (later Blyth Eastman Dillon). Mr. Patton is a director of NuStar GP, LLC (formerly Valero GP, LLC), San Antonio, Texas, and is chairman of its audit committee and a member of its compensation committee. NuStar GP LLC is the
general partner of NuStar Energy L.P. (formerly Valero L.P.), owner and operator of crude oil and refined products pipeline, terminalling, and storage assets. At Apache, Mr. Patton is a member of the Audit Committee.</FONT></TD>

<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>CHARLES J. PITMAN</B>, 70, joined the Company&#146;s Board of Directors in May 2000. Mr.&nbsp;Pitman served as a non-executive director and chairman of Urals Energy Public
Company Limited, an oil exploration and production company operating in Russia, from September 2005 until January 2009, chairman of the board of First Calgary Petroleums Ltd., an oil and gas exploration company engaged in exploration and development
activities in Algeria, from June&nbsp;2007 to March 2008, and was sole member of Shaker Mountain Energy Associates LLC from September 1999 to November 2007. He retired from BP Amoco plc in late 1999, having served as regional president&#151;Middle
East/Caspian/Egypt/India. Prior to the merger of British Petroleum and Amoco Corporation in 1998, Mr. Pitman held a variety of executive positions at Amoco. At Apache, Mr. Pitman is chairman of the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee, a
member of the Stock Plan Committee, and became lead director in February 2013.</FONT></TD>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_13"></A>QUALIFICATIONS OF DIRECTORS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In selecting our directors and director nominees, the CG&amp;N Committee has sought to create a Board with a broad and balanced set of skills,
complemented by diversity of experience and expertise. As is evidenced by the biographical information set forth above, each director contributes his or her own unique background which has led the CG&amp;N Committee to conclude that the Company and
our shareholders will benefit from the director&#146;s service on the Company&#146;s Board. It is equally important that the particular skill sets of each director complement the experience, qualifications, attributes and skills of our Board of
Directors as a whole. In addition to the qualifications described in the preceding biographical information, the following is a discussion of the particular experience, qualifications, attributes or skills of each director that led our Board to
conclude that he or she will contribute to the diversity of experience and expertise required for the effective functioning of our Board. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>G. STEVEN FARRIS </B>Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; 30 years&#146; experience in the oil and gas industry coupled with his 18&nbsp;years of direct leadership at
Apache provide him with valuable insight not only into the oil and gas industry, but also the unique day-to-day operations of Apache. Throughout his career, Mr.&nbsp;Farris has held positions of increasing responsibility in the oil and gas industry,
culminating in his appointment as chief executive officer of Apache in May 2002 and chairman of the board in January 2009. Since being named as chief operating officer in 1994, Mr.&nbsp;Farris has been instrumental in growing the Company&#146;s
reserves by eleven times to approximately 2.9 billion barrels of oil equivalent (&#147;boe&#148;) and production to 778,679 boe per day. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>RANDOLPH M. FERLIC </B>Dr.&nbsp;Ferlic has been involved in research activities throughout his professional life, including in-depth analysis of data,
probabilities, and risks.&nbsp;For his work as a cardiovascular and thoracic surgeon, Dr.&nbsp;Ferlic was awarded &#147;Legend&#148; status by the Nebraska Medical Center and, in February 2011, the &#147;Spirit of the Heart&#148; award by the
American Heart Association. In addition to founding Surgical Services of the Great Plains, from 1974 until 1994, Dr.&nbsp;Ferlic served as the corporation&#146;s president, was responsible for and managed its finances, and was trustee and manager of
the corporation&#146;s employee benefit plans. Dr.&nbsp;Ferlic has twice been publicly elected to the University of Nebraska Board of Regents and has served on its audit committee since 2000. He served as a director and executive committee member on
the Nebraska Medical Center Board, a large hospital system, and was chair of the audit committee from January 2004 until retirement in December 2010. Dr.&nbsp;Ferlic was appointed by both Democrat and Republican governors to serve the past 21 years
as a commissioner for the Midwestern Higher Education Compact, a 12-state policy and business compact for all educational activities in those states.&nbsp;He served as treasurer of the Compact from 1997-2000 and again starting in 2010, and was
elected vice chairman in 2011 and chairman in 2012.&nbsp;His service to both the Compact and the Nebraska Board of Regents has involved shaping policies that help craft strategic and global views. Over the years, Dr.&nbsp;Ferlic has acquired over
300,000 shares of the Company&#146;s common stock for himself and his family, which further aligns him with shareholder interests. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>EUGENE
C. FIEDOREK </B>After working as a petroleum reservoir engineer at Shell Oil Company and British American Oil Producing Company for eight years, Mr.&nbsp;Fiedorek spent 37 years in the oil and gas investment banking and commercial banking
industries. As co-founder, president, and managing director of EnCap Investments and managing director of the Energy Banking Group of First RepublicBank, he gained extensive experience in advising oil and gas companies on their capital structure and
strategic direction. Through these positions, Mr.&nbsp;Fiedorek gained valuable experience in identifying, assessing, and minimizing risk that can affect large oil and gas companies. These positions also provided him with the financial reporting
expertise necessary for his role on Apache&#146;s Audit Committee. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">8 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>A. D. FRAZIER, JR. </B>In addition to the many executive positions noted in his biographical information
above, Mr.&nbsp;Frazier spent a large part of his career as an executive in the investment banking industry. He served as the chief executive officer of INVESCO, Inc., an affiliate of an independent global investment management firm, from 1997 to
2000. Mr.&nbsp;Frazier also served as executive vice president, North American Banking Group, of First Chicago Corporation and First National Bank of Chicago from 1982 to 1991, where, among other numerous industry specialties, he oversaw the
Bank&#146;s oil and gas specialty, which provided him with an intimate knowledge of the oil and gas industry. He also served as the chief operating officer of the Atlanta Olympic Games Committee from 1991 to October 1996, and senior advisor to The
Dilenschneider Group, Inc., a New York-based public relations consulting company, during 2011. During his career, Mr.&nbsp;Frazier has been responsible for the development, management, and operation of a diverse group of businesses and
organizations. Through these executive and director positions, Mr.&nbsp;Frazier gathered extensive experience in identifying, analyzing, and managing risk across a wide range of industries. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>CHANSOO JOUNG</B> Mr.&nbsp;Joung has spent almost his entire career working in the finance industry with energy companies.&nbsp;He currently serves as
a senior advisor at Warburg Pincus LLC where he provides advice on new and existing investments in the energy sector.&nbsp;Previously, as a partner at Warburg Pincus, his duties included sourcing, executing and monitoring energy
investments.&nbsp;Prior to joining Warburg Pincus, Mr.&nbsp;Joung spent almost 18 years at Goldman Sachs where he worked in the Natural Resources Group and also founded and led the London-based European Energy Group in investment banking. While at
Warburg Pincus, Mr.&nbsp;Joung served on the boards of a number of private companies in a variety of sectors in the energy industry. He also served on the boards of Targa Resources Corp. and Targa Resources Partners, LP. Through his experiences in
private equity and as an investment banker, Mr.&nbsp;Joung gained significant experience with energy companies, the energy industry, and energy-related capital markets activity, which enhance his contributions to the Board.&nbsp;Those experiences
have also given Mr.&nbsp;Joung the ability to identify, assess, and manage risk that can affect a large energy company like Apache. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>JOHN A.
KOCUR </B>Mr.&nbsp;Kocur was employed by Apache in various roles from the time that the Company&#146;s stock was first listed on the New York Stock Exchange in 1969 until his retirement in 1991. During his tenure, Mr.&nbsp;Kocur served Apache in
various roles of increasing responsibility, including serving as its general counsel and culminating in his appointment as the Company&#146;s president in 1979. Mr.&nbsp;Kocur, as president and later as vice chairman, was instrumental in overseeing
Apache&#146;s growth from a small drilling program company into a leading independent, international oil and gas company. Mr.&nbsp;Kocur&#146;s unparalleled experience with and understanding of the Company&#146;s history and objectives provide
invaluable insight into the Company&#146;s past, current, and future operations and management.<B> </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>GEORGE D. LAWRENCE
</B>Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence began his oil and gas career with the predecessor to The Phoenix Resource Companies, Inc. in 1985, holding management positions with increasing responsibility, culminating in his serving as president, chief executive officer,
and a director of Phoenix from 1990 until 1996, when the company merged with Apache. During his tenure as chief executive officer of Phoenix, Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence gained valuable corporate leadership experience in all aspects of business including
finance, securities, operations, strategy, and&nbsp;risk.&nbsp;At Phoenix and its predecessor, Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence was extensively involved in international operations that were spread over several continents and&nbsp;he was especially instrumental in
leading Phoenix&#146;s operations in Egypt, an area that remains at the core of Apache&#146;s operations.&nbsp;Prior to entering the oil and gas business, Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence engaged&nbsp;in a diversified private practice of law and also&nbsp;served
five years&nbsp;at the United States Department of Justice, his last position there being the assistant chief of the environmental enforcement section. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">9 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>WILLIAM C. MONTGOMERY </B>Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery has spent almost his entire career working in the finance
industry focusing on large cap energy companies.&nbsp;He currently serves as a managing director at Quantum Energy Partners where he provides advice on new and existing investments in the energy and power industries.&nbsp;At Quantum, his duties
include membership on the executive and investment committees, which set the firm&#146;s strategy and originate and oversee investments in the upstream, midstream, and oilfield service sectors of the oil and gas industry.&nbsp;Previously, as a
partner at Goldman, Sachs&nbsp;&amp; Co. for over eight years, he headed the Americas Natural Resources Group and was a member of the Investment Banking Services Leadership Group.&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery&#146;s contributions to the Board will be
aided by the knowledge and experience he gains from his current role at Quantum Energy Partners, which involves broad and deep exposure to key issues impacting the upstream, midstream, and oil services sectors. His contributions to the Board will
also be enhanced by his background as an investment banker, where he gained significant experience with the energy industry and energy-related capital markets. Apache will also benefit from the extensive relationships that Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery has
formed throughout his 22-year career serving various global energy companies. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>RODMAN D. PATTON </B>Prior to joining the Company&#146;s
Board of Directors, for over 25 years, Mr.&nbsp;Patton held various executive positions in the oil and gas investment banking industry. As a managing director at Merrill Lynch, First Boston (later Credit Suisse) and other investment banks,
Mr.&nbsp;Patton gained extensive experience advising oil and gas companies on capital structure, strategy, and direction. He also gained valuable experience in the assessment and management of risk faced by oil and gas companies. As a former
investment banker and as chairman of NuStar GP&#146;s audit committee, Mr.&nbsp;Patton has extensive financial reporting expertise, which serves him well in his role as a member of Apache&#146;s Audit Committee. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>CHARLES J. PITMAN </B>Having served in executive and director capacities at numerous oil and gas companies, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman has gained invaluable
experience in and knowledge of the oil and gas industry. During his 24-year career at Amoco Corporation and BP Amoco plc, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman served in a variety of leadership positions in the United States and multiple international locations,
principally in the Middle East. Notably, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman served as president of Amoco Egypt Oil Company from 1992 to 1996, president of Amoco Eurasia Petroleum Company from 1997 to 1998, regional president BP Amoco plc&nbsp;&#151; Middle
East/Caspian/Egypt/India from December 1998 until his retirement in 1999. Most recently, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman has utilized his considerable experience in international oil and gas by participating in oil and gas ventures in Russia and Algeria. Prior to
joining Amoco, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman served in the United States Department of State as a foreign service officer and attorney-adviser. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">10 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_14"></A>DIRECTOR INDEPENDENCE </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">During 2012 and the first two months of 2013, the Board of Directors evaluated all business and charitable relationships between the Company and the
Company&#146;s non-employee directors (all directors other than Mr.&nbsp;Farris) and all other relevant facts and circumstances. As a result of the evaluation, the Board of Directors determined, as required by the Company&#146;s Governance
Principles, that each non-employee director is an independent director as defined by the standards for director independence established by applicable laws, rules, and listing standards including, without limitation, the standards for independent
directors established by The New York Stock Exchange, Inc. (&#147;NYSE&#148;), The NASDAQ National Market (&#147;NASDAQ&#148;), and the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#147;SEC&#148;). The Company&#146;s Governance Principles are available on
the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Subject to some exceptions, these standards generally provide that a non-employee director
will not be independent if (a)&nbsp;the director is, or in the past three years has been, an employee of the Company; (b)&nbsp;the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family is, or in the past three years has been, an executive
officer of the Company; (c)&nbsp;the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family has received more than $120,000 per year in direct compensation from the Company (other than for service as a director or for the immediate family
member, as a non-executive employee); (d)&nbsp;the director is an employee of or the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family is employed as a partner of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP, the Company&#146;s independent registered
public accountants, or the director has an immediate family member who is a current employee of such firm and works in any capacity on the Company&#146;s audit, or the director or an immediate family member was within the last three years a partner
or employee of such firm and personally worked on the Company&#146;s audit within that time; (e)&nbsp;the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family is, or in the past three years has been, employed as an executive officer of a
company where an Apache executive officer serves on the compensation committee; or (f)&nbsp;the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family is an executive officer of a company that makes payments to, or receives payments from,
Apache in an amount which, in any twelve-month period during the past three years, exceeds the greater of $200,000 or two percent of the consolidated gross revenues of the company receiving the payment. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Lead Director </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company&#146;s
Governance Principles require that the independent (non-employee) directors meet in executive session at least twice each year and, in 2012, they met five times in executive session. These executive sessions are chaired by a lead director. Pursuant
to the Company&#146;s Governance Principles, the lead director is an independent director who is elected from time to time, but not less than annually, by the affirmative vote of a majority of the non-management directors. In addition to chairing
the executive sessions, the lead director discusses management&#146;s proposed meeting agenda with the other independent directors and reviews the approved meeting agenda with our chairman and chief executive officer, leads the discussion with our
chief executive officer following the independent directors&#146; executive sessions, ensures that the Board&#146;s individual group, and committee self-assessments are done annually, leads periodic discussions with other Board members and
management concerning the Board&#146;s information needs, and is available for discussions with major shareholders. Randolph M. Ferlic served as lead director from February 2011 until February 2013. In November 2012, effective February 2013, Charles
J. Pitman was elected as lead director. The role and responsibilities of the lead director and the method established for communication of concerns to the independent directors are included in the Company&#146;s Governance Principles. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">11 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Reporting of Concerns to Independent Directors </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Anyone who has concerns about the Company may communicate those concerns to the independent directors. Such communication should be mailed to the
Company&#146;s corporate secretary at 2000 Post Oak Boulevard, Suite 100, Houston, Texas 77056-4400, who will forward such communications to the independent directors. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Board Leadership Structure and Risk Oversight </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Board Leadership
Structure </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Throughout much of Apache&#146;s history, the Company has ascribed to the traditional U.S. board leadership structure, under
which our chief executive officer has also served as the chairman of our Board of Directors. From 1969 until 2002, both of these positions were held by our founder, Mr.&nbsp;Raymond Plank. However, upon Mr.&nbsp;Raymond Plank&#146;s retirement as
chief executive officer of the Company in 2002, Mr.&nbsp;Farris was appointed as the Company&#146;s chief executive officer and Mr.&nbsp;Raymond Plank remained as the Company&#146;s chairman of the board. Upon Mr.&nbsp;Plank&#146;s retirement as
chairman of the board in January 2009, Mr.&nbsp;Farris was appointed the Company&#146;s chairman of the board, once again unifying the roles of chairman and chief executive officer. As Apache&#146;s history demonstrates, we believe it is important
to maintain the flexibility to have either a combined or a separated chair and chief executive officer structure as circumstances dictate.&nbsp;Each structure has served us well in the past. Currently, we believe that the efficiencies created by a
combined position work best, especially when viewed in conjunction with our lead director, elected annually by our independent directors, assuring strong board leadership.&nbsp;In particular, this structure helps to ensure clarity regarding
leadership of the Company, allows the Company to speak with one voice and provides for efficient coordination of board action, particularly in the event of crisis. The combination of the chairman&#146;s ability to call board meetings with the chief
executive officer&#146;s intimate knowledge of our business, including our risk management framework, provides a strong structure for the efficient operation of our board process and effective leadership of our Board overall. This structure avoids
potential confusion as to leadership roles and duplication of efforts that can result from the roles being separated. It also assists our chairman and chief executive officer in managing the Company and dealing with third parties more effectively on
a day-to-day basis. Our Board regularly reviews all the aspects of our governance profile, including this one, and will make changes as circumstances warrant. This is the model that the Company has utilized for much of its history, and we believe
that it is the most effective way to lead the Company going forward. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Risk Oversight </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The goal of the Company&#146;s risk management process is to understand and manage risk; management is responsible for identifying and managing the risks,
while directors provide oversight to management in this process. Management identifies the significant risks facing the Company and the approaches to mitigate such risk. The Company&#146;s Governance Principles state that in addition to its general
oversight of management, the Board of Directors is responsible for a number of specific functions, including assessing major risks facing the Company and reviewing options for their mitigation. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our Board of Directors has five standing independent committees: Audit, Corporate Governance and Nominating, Management Development and Compensation,
Executive, and Stock Plan. Our Audit Committee is primarily responsible for overseeing the Company&#146;s risk management processes on behalf of the Board. The Audit Committee charter provides that the Audit Committee should discuss and consider the
process by which senior management of the Company and the relevant departments assess and manage the Company&#146;s exposure to risk, and discuss the Company&#146;s major financial risk exposure
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">12 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">
and the steps management has taken to monitor, control, and report such exposures. In addition, the Audit Committee reports to the Board of Directors, which also considers the Company&#146;s risk
profile. The Audit Committee and the Board of Directors obtain input from management regarding the most significant risks facing the Company and the Company&#146;s risk management strategy. The Audit Committee and the Board ensure that the risks
undertaken are consistent with the Board&#146;s tolerance for risk. While the Board is responsible for setting, monitoring and maintaining the Company&#146;s risk management policies and practices, the Company&#146;s executive officers and members
of our management team are responsible for implementing and overseeing our day-to-day risk management processes. Additionally, the Board has created a Corporate Risk Committee composed of members of our management team. The Corporate Risk Committee
monitors and manages risks and is tasked with, among other things, ensuring sound policies, procedures, and practices are in place to address corporate-wide management of risks. The Company believes that this division of responsibility is the most
effective way to monitor and control risk. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In addition to the oversight provided by our full Board of Directors, Audit Committee, executive
officers and the members of our management team, including our Corporate Risk Committee, our independent (non-employee) directors hold regularly scheduled executive sessions as often as they deem appropriate, but in any event at least twice each
year. These executive sessions are chaired by our lead director, and provide an additional avenue through which we monitor the Company&#146;s risk exposure and policies regarding risk management. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Risk Considerations in Our Compensation Programs </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our Management Development and Compensation (&#147;MD&amp;C&#148;) Committee has discussed the concept of risk as it relates to our compensation programs, and the MD&amp;C Committee does not believe our
compensation programs encourage excessive or inappropriate risk taking. The MD&amp;C Committee, with assistance of its independent compensation consultant (as discussed in the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; below), arrived at this
conclusion for the following reasons: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our employees receive both fixed and variable compensation. The fixed (salary) portion provides a steady income regardless of the Company&#146;s stock
performance. This allows executives to focus on the Company&#146;s business without an excessive focus on the Company&#146;s stock price performance. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The goals and objectives for the annual cash incentive bonus are set to avoid overweighting any single factor that, if not achieved, would result in
the loss of a large percentage of compensation. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our stock options and restricted stock units generally vest over four years, which discourages short-term risk taking. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our equity ownership requirements encourage a long-term perspective by our executives. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">All of our executives&#146; unvested long-term equity compensation is forfeited upon voluntary termination, which encourages our executives to remain
with the Company and maintain a long-term focus. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our incentive programs have been in place for many years, and we have seen no evidence that they encourage excessive risk taking.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Essentially all of our employees participate in our equity-based compensation programs, regardless of business unit which encourages consistent
behavior across the Company. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">13 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_15"></A>STANDING COMMITTEES AND MEETINGS OF THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Board of Directors has an Audit Committee, a Corporate Governance and Nominating (&#147;CG&amp;N&#148;) Committee, an MD&amp;C
Committee, a Stock Plan Committee, and an Executive Committee. Actions taken by these committees are reported to the Board of Directors at the next board meeting. During 2012, each of the Company&#146;s current directors attended at least 75 percent
of all meetings of the Board of Directors and committees of which he or she was a member. All directors attended the Company&#146;s 2012 annual meeting of shareholders held on May&nbsp;24, 2012. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence was appointed chairman of the MD&amp;C Committee in February 2012. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>  <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Audit Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Audit Committee reviews, with the independent public accountants and
internal auditors of the Company, their respective audit and review programs and procedures and the scope and results of their audits. It also examines professional services provided by the Company&#146;s independent public accountants and evaluates
their costs and related fees. Additionally, the Audit Committee reviews the Company&#146;s financial statements and the adequacy of the Company&#146;s system of internal controls over financial reporting. As described more fully above in &#147;Board
Leadership Structure and Risk Oversight,&#148; the Audit Committee is also tasked with overseeing the guidelines, policies, and controls governing the process by which management of the Company assesses and manages the Company&#146;s exposure to
risk. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">14 </FONT></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">
The Audit Committee has the sole authority to appoint, compensate, retain, oversee, and terminate our independent auditors. It also has the sole authority to pre-approve all terms of and set fees
for audit services, audit related services, tax services, and other services to be performed for the Company by the Company&#146;s independent registered public accountants. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">During 2012 and the first two months of 2013, the Board of Directors reviewed the composition of the Audit Committee pursuant to the rules of the NYSE and NASDAQ governing audit committees. Based on this
review, the Board of Directors confirmed that all members of the Audit Committee are &#147;independent&#148; under the NYSE and NASDAQ rules. The Audit Committee charter, which reflects applicable NYSE and SEC rules and regulations, is available on
the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). The Board of Directors has determined that all members of the Audit Committee qualify as financial experts, as defined in Item&nbsp;407 of Regulation S-K under the Securities Act of 1933. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>MD&amp;C Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The MD&amp;C
Committee reviews the Company&#146;s management resources and structure and administers the Company&#146;s compensation programs and retirement, stock purchase and similar plans. Under the provisions of its charter, the MD&amp;C Committee may, at
its discretion and if allowed by applicable laws or regulations, delegate all or a portion of its duties and responsibilities to a subcommittee of the MD&amp;C Committee composed of at least two members. During 2012 and the first two months of 2013,
the Board of Directors reviewed the composition of the MD&amp;C Committee pursuant to the rules of the NYSE and NASDAQ governing compensation committees. Based on this review, the Board of Directors confirmed that all members of the MD&amp;C
Committee are &#147;independent&#148; under the NYSE and NASDAQ rules. The MD&amp;C Committee charter is available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>CG&amp;N Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The duties of the CG&amp;N Committee include recommending to the Board
of Directors the slate of director nominees submitted to the shareholders for election at each annual meeting and proposing qualified candidates to fill vacancies on the Board of Directors. The CG&amp;N Committee is also responsible for developing
corporate governance principles for the Company, reviewing related party transactions, and overseeing the evaluation of the Board of Directors. During 2012 and the first two months of 2013, the Board of Directors reviewed the composition of the
CG&amp;N Committee pursuant to the rules of the NYSE and NASDAQ governing nominating and governance committees. Based on this review, the Board of Directors confirmed that all members of the CG&amp;N Committee are &#147;independent&#148; under the
NYSE and NASDAQ rules. The CG&amp;N Committee charter is available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The CG&amp;N Committee
considers director nominee recommendations from executive officers of the Company, independent members of the Board and shareholders of the Company, as well as recommendations from other interested parties. The CG&amp;N Committee may also retain an
outside search firm to assist it in finding appropriate nominee candidates. Shareholder recommendations for director nominees received by Apache&#146;s corporate secretary (at the address for submitting shareholder proposals and nominations set
forth under the heading &#147;Future Shareholder Proposals and Director Nominations&#148; below) are forwarded to the CG&amp;N Committee for consideration. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">15 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Stock Plan Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In July 2011, the Board of Directors formed a fifth standing independent committee, the Stock Plan Committee, to replace the Stock Option Plan Committee, which was a subcommittee of the MD&amp;C
Committee. The Stock Plan Committee charter is available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). The principal purpose of the Stock Plan Committee is to assist the Board of Directors in the discharge of its responsibilities related to
equity-based compensation for the Company&#146;s employees, including the named executive officers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The three members of the Stock Plan
Committee are &#147;outside directors&#148; as defined by applicable federal tax law or regulations of the Internal Revenue Service. The duties of the Stock Plan Committee include (i)&nbsp;administration of the Company&#146;s equity-based
compensation plans and programs and approval, award, and administration of grants made thereunder, (ii)&nbsp;certification of performance goals and their achievement, (iii)&nbsp;making recommendations to the Board of Directors with respect to the
Company&#146;s equity-based compensation plans and programs, and (iv)&nbsp;any other duties and responsibilities expressly delegated to the Stock Plan Committee by the Board of Directors relating to equity-based compensation plans and programs.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Executive Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The
Executive Committee is vested with the authority to exercise the full power of the Board of Directors, within established policies, in the intervals between meetings of the Board of Directors. In addition to the general authority vested in it, the
Executive Committee may be vested with specific powers and authority by resolution of the Board of Directors. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Committee Charters
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">As noted above, you can access electronic copies of the charters of the Audit Committee, CG&amp;N Committee, MD&amp;C Committee, and Stock
Plan Committee of the Board of Directors on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). Also available on the Company&#146;s website are our Governance Principles and our Code of Business Conduct, which meets the requirements of a code of
ethics under applicable SEC regulations and NYSE and NASDAQ standards. You may request printed copies of any of these documents by writing to Apache&#146;s corporate secretary at 2000 Post Oak Boulevard, Suite&nbsp;100, Houston, Texas 77056-4400.
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">16 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_16"></A>CRITERIA FOR NEW BOARD MEMBERS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>AND RE-ELECTION OF BOARD MEMBERS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The CG&amp;N Committee considers the following criteria in recommending new nominees or the re-election of directors to the Company&#146;s Board of Directors and its committees: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Expertise and perspective needed to govern the business and strengthen and support senior management &#151; for example: strong financial expertise,
knowledge of international operations, or knowledge of the petroleum industry and/or related industries. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Sound business judgment and a sufficiently broad perspective to make meaningful contributions. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Interest and enthusiasm in the Company and a commitment to become involved in its future. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The time and energy to meet Board of Directors commitments. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Ability to constructively participate in discussions, with the capacity to quickly understand and evaluate complex and diverse issues.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Dedication to the highest ethical standards. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Supportive of management, but independent, objective, and willing to question and challenge both openly and in private exchanges.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">An awareness of the dynamics of change and a willingness to anticipate and explore opportunities. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">All decisions to recommend the nomination of a new nominee for election to the Board of Directors or for the re-election of a director are within the sole
discretion of the CG&amp;N Committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">All director candidates are evaluated, and the decision of whether or not to nominate a particular
candidate is made, based solely on Company- and work-related factors and not with regard to a candidate&#146;s or director&#146;s inclusion in any protected class or group identified in the Company&#146;s anti-discrimination policy. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The above criteria and guidelines, together with the section of the Company&#146;s Governance Principles entitled &#147;Qualifications of Board
Members&#148; constitute the policy of the CG&amp;N Committee regarding the recommendation of new nominees or the re-election of directors to the Company&#146;s Board of Directors or its committees. The Company&#146;s Governance Principles are
available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Diversity </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Company policy precludes directors and employees from discriminating against any protected group. Company policy also precludes directors and employees from basing work-related decisions on anything other
than work-relevant criteria.&nbsp;The Company&#146;s approach to diversity complements these policies without conflicting with them. Our status as a global company makes the need for board diversity in all its aspects essential to our
business.&nbsp;Our criteria for board selection, summarized in this section, operates as our diversity policy. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">17 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
