<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Using judgment to determine where a particular executive&#146;s salary falls within the salary ranges. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">40 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">We review base salaries continually with a view towards considering adjustment every 12 to 18&nbsp;months,
but base salary reviews may occur more or less frequently depending on Apache, market conditions, and individual performance. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_16">
</A>Annual Cash Incentive Bonus </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our executive officers are eligible to earn an annual cash incentive bonus. We set annual cash incentive
bonus targets hierarchically as a multiple of base salary, with target multiples increasing with the level of responsibility of the executive. The percentage of target actually awarded to our corporate executive officers is determined as a function
of a combination of (i)&nbsp;our achievement of a variety of financial, operational, and management objectives, which we refer to as corporate performance goals and corporate management objectives, respectively, and (ii)&nbsp;each officer&#146;s
individual achievement of job-specific goals and overall performance. The chairman and chief executive officer evaluates officers with regional responsibilities based on their region&#146;s production, revenue, costs, and other regional results.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Corporate Performance Element </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">We equally weight the achievement of our corporate performance goals and our corporate management objectives in our evaluation of the annual incentive award for each of the named executive officers.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Corporate Performance Goals</I>: The corporate performance goals are a set of objective standards that are established each year for production
growth, reserve growth, earnings, cash flow, and lifting costs per boe. These goals may be modified from time to time by the MD&amp;C Committee to appropriately reflect acquisitions, dispositions, and other major events. Each corporate performance
goal represents approximately 5 to 15 percent of an officer&#146;s annual cash incentive bonus. For each corporate performance goal, the executive officers can be awarded full credit if Apache achieves the goal, potential partial credit if Apache
makes significant progress towards the goal, and extra credit if Apache exceeds the goal due to the extraordinary nature of these achievements. The ambitious corporate performance goals we set for 2012 were impacted by the considerable decline in
natural gas prices experienced in North America that led to write downs of our natural gas reserves in Canada. These non-cash write downs negatively impacted our earnings and reserves. Accordingly, we partially met only one of the five corporate
performance goals. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Production</I>: Our goal was to grow production 6 percent (after accounting for 2011 divestitures). In 2012, we grew production 5.4 percent (after
accounting for 2011 divestitures), partially meeting this goal. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Earnings</I>: Our goal was earning at least $4.5 billion. Largely as a result of the write down of natural gas reserves in Canada, we did not
achieve our earnings goal. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Reserves</I>: Our goal was to grow reserves by 5 percent. In 2012, we did not meet this goal as a result of the write down of the reserves in
Canada. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Cash Flow</I>: Our goal was to generate annual cash flow</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">4</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"> of at least $10.23 billion. While our cash flow was impacted by the depressed North American natural gas prices, we
generated $10.25 billion, which however, was just shy of this goal on a per share basis. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="line-height:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000;width:10%">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">4</SUP>&nbsp;</FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Adjusted earnings and cash flow are non-GAAP financial measures, as defined in Regulation G promulgated by the SEC. Adjusted earnings is net income (loss) attributable
to common stock adjusted for certain items that management believes affect the comparability of operating results, such as foreign currency fluctuation impact on deferred tax expense, merger, acquisitions and transitions costs, net of tax, deferred
tax adjustments, commodity derivative mark-to-market gains or losses, and additional depletion, net of tax. A reconciliation of adjusted earnings to net income for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2012, is contained in item 7 of our Annual Report on
Form 10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2012. Cash flow is cash from operations before changes in operating assets and liabilities. A reconciliation of cash flow to net cash provided by operating activities for the year ended
December&nbsp;31, 2012, was previously furnished to the SEC in our Current Report on Form 8-K dated February&nbsp;14, 2013. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">41 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>LOE per BOE</I>: Our goal was to maintain direct lifting costs per boe produced at the 2011 levels of $9.54 per boe. In 2012, we did not achieve
this goal as our lifting costs were $10.41/boe. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Corporate Management Objectives</I>: Our corporate management objectives include a comprehensive list of strategic and tactical goals developed and
weighted by management and approved by the MD&amp;C Committee at the beginning of each year. These objectives are then reviewed and, if appropriate, modified through the year as circumstances dictate and as approved by the MD&amp;C Committee. Each
basic corporate management objective represents no more than 4 percent of an officer&#146;s annual cash incentive bonus. The MD&amp;C Committee has discretion in determining the relative success of the corporate management objectives. Points for
each goal vary based on the relative importance of each goal, and are awarded upon achievement.&nbsp;In the case of certain objectives, partial or extra credit may be awarded based on the extent of goal achievement. In addition to the tactical
goals, executives are eligible to receive extra credit for attainment of extraordinary objectives. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Individual
Performance Element </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The foundation of our annual cash incentive bonuses is our achievement of the corporate performance goals and
corporate management objectives. We believe that annual cash incentive bonuses are most effective when they are carefully tailored to job responsibilities of individual executives. The MD&amp;C Committee receives input from the chairman and chief
executive officer on the individual performance of each executive officer other than himself. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_17"></A>Long-Term
Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Long-term, equity-based compensation is regularly made available to substantially all of our employees to ensure a
company-wide ethic of ownership and entrepreneurialism. Properly designed long-term, equity-based compensation aligns the interests of executive officers and employees with those of our shareholders and plays an important role in our overall
compensation structure. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">We annually grant a combination of RSUs, stock options, and Performance Shares, the overall grant value of which is
based on a hierarchical multiple of salary. The multiple of salary for each executive is determined based on the executive&#146;s level in the organization and is adjusted periodically as necessary to align the total compensation of our executives
with the market. The multiples for long-term compensation increase as the level of responsibility rises. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Long-term compensation awarded to our
executive officers is presently apportioned in accordance with targeted grant date values as follows: Performance Shares (35 percent), RSUs (35 percent), and stock options (30 percent). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Performance Shares </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Each January, our named executive officers receive Performance
shares under our TSR Program. Under the TSR Program: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">We issue conditional awards to substantially all of our management and senior level professional employees, including each named executive officer,
based on a target percentage of the grantee&#146;s then annual base salary; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Each TSR Program has a three-year performance period, at the end of which a calculation of total shareholder return (&#147;TSR&#148;) performance is
determined for Apache and each member of the Performance Peer Group (defined below) by dividing (i)&nbsp;the sum of the cumulative amount of each company&#146;s dividends for the performance period (assuming same-day reinvestment into the
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">42 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">
company&#146;s common stock on the ex-dividend date) and the average per share closing price of each company&#146;s stock for the 60 trading days at the end of the performance period minus the
average per share closing price of each company&#146;s stock for the 60 trading days preceding the beginning of the performance period; by (ii)&nbsp;the average per share closing price of each company&#146;s stock for the 60 trading days preceding
the beginning of the performance period; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our TSR performance is directly ranked against the Performance Peer Group, resulting in the application of a payout factor to the target number of
Performance Shares to derive the adjusted number of RSUs that will actually be paid at the end of the performance period; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The resulting shares vest over time, with 50 percent of the shares vesting at the end of the three-year performance period, and the remaining 50
percent vesting equally over the following two years; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Employees must be employed at the time of each vesting to receive vested shares; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">If a change of control and a recipient&#146;s involuntary termination or voluntary termination with cause (double trigger) occur (i)&nbsp;during the
performance period, the TSR is calculated and our TSR performance is ranked within the Performance Peer Group as of the date of termination; (ii)&nbsp;during the vesting period, the entire amount of the award vests as of the date of termination.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The peer companies for each performance period (the &#147;Performance Peer Group&#148;) are determined prior to commencement
of the period and comprise a larger group of companies than our Compensation Peer Group. We use an expanded list of performance peer companies for the following reasons: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><U>Comparison</U>: The broader Performance Peer Group provides a more appropriate basis for judging our corporate performance than the more narrowly
focused Compensation Peer Group. The Compensation Peer Group consists, in large part, of companies whose principle business is North American oil and/or natural gas and who are our predominant competition for executive talent. As approximately 44
percent of our production is outside of North America and approximately 45 percent of our production is crude oil, it is more appropriate to have a larger, more diversified peer group to benchmark our corporate performance. The expanded Performance
Peer Group includes many companies we compete against internationally. The overall risks and opportunities faced by this larger group more closely match ours than those faced by the less diverse Compensation Peer Group. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><U>Continuation</U>: Because it is not unusual that one or two companies in our Compensation Peer Group may cease to exist during a three-year
performance period through merger or otherwise, the expanded group provides more stability and longevity to the TSR Program. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><U>Statistical Reliability and Validity</U>: The larger Performance Peer Group provides a more stable and valid statistical yardstick for the TSR
Program. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><U>2012 TSR Program Payout Factor</U>: Under our 2012 TSR Program, a rank of one results in a multiple of 2.5 with the multiple grading down to 0.5 for a
ranking of 13, and a multiple of 0.0 for a ranking below&nbsp;13. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><U>2013 TSR Program</U> </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Performance Peer Group for the 2013 TSR Program, pursuant to which grants were awarded in January 2013, is the same as the one for our 2012 TSR
Program. Under our 2013 TSR Program a rank of one results in a multiple of 2.0 with the multiple grading down to 0.55 for a ranking of 15, and a multiple of 0.0 for a ranking below 15. We adjusted the payout multiples for our 2013 TSR Program to
drive the grant date value of the payout as close to 1.0 as possible. </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Restricted Stock Units </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Each May, our employees, including our named executive officers, receive RSUs, currently under the 2011 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan. Generally, the RSUs: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Are granted to substantially our entire employee population, including our executive officers, based on a target percentage of the grantee&#146;s then
annual base salary; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Vest ratably over four years; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Upon vesting, allow each grantee to receive one share of common stock for each RSU; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Require a double trigger for accelerated vesting (both a change of control and a recipient&#146;s involuntary termination or voluntary termination with
cause); and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Are forfeited if they are unvested and the executive voluntarily terminates or is terminated for cause prior to the vesting date.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Stock Options </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Each May, our employees, including our named executive officers, also receive stock option grants, currently under the 2011 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan. Generally, our stock options: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Are granted to approximately half of our employees, including our named executive officers, based on a target percentage of the grantee&#146;s then
annual base salary; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Benefit the recipient only if shareholders also benefit from appreciating stock prices; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Become exercisable ratably over a four-year period; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Have an exercise price equal to the closing price of our common stock on the date of grant and expire 10 years after grant;
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Require a double trigger for accelerated vesting (both a change of control and a recipient&#146;s involuntary termination or voluntary termination with
cause); and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Cannot be repriced or reset or exchanged for cash, if they are underwater (exercise price is greater than current stock price).
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The grants of Performance Shares, RSUs, and stock options made in 2012 to the named executive officers are reflected in the
&#147;Grants of Plan-Based Awards Table.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Stock Ownership Requirements </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">To further align the interests of our directors and officers with those of our shareholders, we have stock ownership requirements for both directors and
officers. Since 2007, we have had minimum stock ownership requirements for our Board of Directors, and in November 2009, we adopted a two-part stock ownership policy for our officers. Officers are expected to meet these requirements within three
years of being appointed or promoted to their position. In the event of a base salary increase, officers have one year to meet their increased requirement. All of the directors and the named executive officers currently meet these requirements.
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">45 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Salary Multiple Requirement </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">One part of the stock ownership policy requires that each officer own at least the number of shares of our common stock equal to a multiple of the officer&#146;s base salary, measured against the value of
the officer&#146;s holdings, based on the average per share closing price of our common stock for the previous year. After achieving the minimum stock ownership requirements, each officer must continue to meet the minimum stock ownership
requirements for his or her current office. The ownership requirements are: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="92%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Requirement</B></FONT></TD></TR>

<TR BGCOLOR="#cccccc">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Executive Vice Presidents and Senior Vice Presidents</FONT></P></TD>

Presidents, Regional Vice Presidents, and Staff Vice Presidents</FONT></P></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" NOWRAP ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">2.0x Base Salary</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In determining stock ownership levels, we include: Shares purchased in the open market; vested shares in qualified and
non-qualified plans; shares obtained through stock option exercises that the officer continues to hold; the vested portion of RSUs and restricted stock; shares beneficially owned in a trust or partnership, by a spouse, and/or minor child; and shares
held in the Apache&#146;s Deferred Delivery Plan. Unearned Performance Shares, unvested RSUs, unvested shares of restricted stock, and unexercised stock options are not counted toward meeting the requirements. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Percentage of Equity Award Requirement </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">A second stock ownership test requires each officer to hold at least 15 percent of all restricted and performance shares he or she receives, net of tax
withholding, until such officer retires or otherwise terminates his or her employment. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_18"></A>Benefits </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our named executive officers receive the standard benefits received by all employees including: group health (medical, dental, pharmacy and vision), group
life, accidental death and dismemberment, business travel accident, disability plans, defined contribution retirement plans (a Money Purchase Retirement Plan and a 401(k) Savings Plan), and vacation. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>General Executive Policies </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">As
part of their total compensation, our named executive officers are eligible for additional benefits that are designed to maintain market competitiveness. These include a comprehensive annual physical examination, an individual cash-value-based
variable universal life insurance policy of two times base salary, an enhanced individual long-term disability policy of 75 percent of eligible earnings, and continued Apache and employee tax deferred contributions to a non-qualified
retirement/savings plan once limits are reached in qualified retirement plans. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Use of Property </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our operations are spread around the globe, including in locations that present a variety of physical and geo-political risks. For both business
efficiency and security reasons, we require the chairman and chief executive officer to use Apache&#146;s aircraft for all air travel, unless good business judgment would require otherwise. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">More details on the above benefits are presented under &#147;All Other Compensation&#148; following the &#147;Summary Compensation Table.&#148; </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">46 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_19"></A>COMPENSATION DECISIONS IN 2012 </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The following discussion sets forth decisions regarding 2012 compensation for our named executive officers: Messrs. Farris, Plank, Eichler, Lannie, and
Chambers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_20"></A>Experience and Responsibilities </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Chairman and Chief Executive Officer </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Farris joined Apache in 1988, and was
named chief executive officer in May 2002 and chairman of the board in January 2009. His leadership responsibilities include developing sustainable global strategies, recommending and implementing our capital expenditure programs, developing and
maintaining sound business relationships with many of the world&#146;s major energy companies, developing and maintaining good relationships with the shareholder, investment, and policy-making communities, guiding and developing senior management,
and overseeing our major business and staff units. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; direct reports include each of the other named executive officers,
except for Mr.&nbsp;Chambers, who reports to Mr.&nbsp;Plank. Also reporting directly to Mr.&nbsp;Farris are our executive vice president and chief technology officer, executive vice president of corporate reservoir engineering, executive vice
president of human resources, executive vice president of international operations, vice president of worldwide exploration and new ventures, senior vice president and chief of staff, planning and strategy, and vice president of environmental health
and safety. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Other Named Executive Officers </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Messrs. Plank, Eichler, Lannie, and Chambers have served us for a combined 78 years. During this period, each of them has made significant contributions to Apache. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Plank, our president and chief corporate officer, has been employed by Apache for 31 years and has been instrumental in managing our financial
health, including management of complex financial matters related to our expansion into a global enterprise. The scope of his responsibilities has continued to grow as Apache has grown and as the number of legal and financial jurisdictions in which
we operate has multiplied. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Eichler, our president and chief operating officer, has been employed by Apache for 19 years and oversees our worldwide operations. Under his
leadership, Apache obtained record production results this year despite facing economic and operational challenges in some of its regions. Previously, he had responsibility for our international operating regions consisting of Egypt, Australia,
United Kingdom, and Argentina, and prior to that time he headed our operations in Egypt for 12 years. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Lannie, our executive vice president and general counsel, has been employed by Apache for 10 years. Prior to his tenure at Apache, he held

instrumental in the numerous transactions that have advanced our growth. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_21"></A>Base Salary Actions </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Chairman and Chief Executive Officer </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; base salary for 2012 was $1,750,000. He did not receive an increase in his base salary during 2012 or 2011. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Other Named Executive Officers </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">To make base salary adjustment recommendations for
the named executive officers other than the chairman and chief executive officer, the MD&amp;C Committee begins with input from the chairman and chief executive officer concerning the individual performance of each executive and his input concerning
the optimal application of the data and policies used (and summarized above) to establish salary ranges more generally. The MD&amp;C Committee reviews this information and analyzes how the base salary and contemplated adjustments for each named
executive officer aligns with market data, our performance, market conditions, and internal pay parity considerations. In November 2012, the Committee awarded salary increases to Messrs. Lannie and Chambers in conjunction with their periodic salary
review. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The table below reflects the base salaries of our named executive officers approved by the board in 2012: </FONT></P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_22"></A>2012 Annual Cash Incentive Bonus Awards </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The 2012 annual cash incentive bonus for the named executive officers was comprised of a corporate performance element and an individual performance
element. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Corporate Performance Element </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The corporate performance element is composed of our achievement of our: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Corporate performance goals, and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Corporate management objectives. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">For a discussion of each element please see &#147;Annual Cash Incentive Bonus &#151; <I>Corporate Performance Goals</I> &#151; <I>Corporate Management Objectives</I>&#148;. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">After its evaluation, the MD&amp;C Committee determined that we achieved 22 percent of our corporate performance goals in 2012, and 110 percent of our
corporate management objectives. As a result, the total aggregate achievement of our corporate performance goals and corporate management objectives was 66 percent, comprised of 11 percent for our corporate performance goals and 55 percent for our
corporate management objectives. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">48 </FONT></P>

of factors that it will consider to enhance its evaluation of the chairman and chief executive officer. While the MD&amp;C Committee does not assign specific weights to the factors below, it uses them to gain additional perspective in evaluating the
individual performance of the chairman and chief executive officer. The factors include: </FONT></P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Other factors as deemed appropriate
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE></DIV><div style="clear:both; height:0px; font-size:0px">&nbsp;</div>
 <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The MD&amp;C Committee also
considered other subjective factors including the scope of our chairman and chief executive officer&#146;s responsibilities, the leadership qualities exhibited by him among the executive team and the organization in general, the relationships
nurtured by him with shareholders, industry partners, governments, and other stakeholders, the soundness of judgment exhibited by him in the development and execution of corporate strategy, the effectiveness of his judgment in the allocation of
financial capital, the deployment and development of human capital, the management of risk, the long-term realization of our corporate management objectives, our multi-year comprehensive performance, the position and strength of Apache relative to
peers, and the level of annual earnings, cash flow and direct lifting costs. </FONT></P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our chairman and chief executive officer&#146;s annual cash
incentive bonus was targeted at 200 percent of his base salary earnings. We considered all of the above factors when setting his annual cash incentive bonus without assigning specific weights to each of them. The Board, pursuant to the
recommendation of the MD&amp;C Committee, awarded our chairman and chief executive officer an annual cash incentive bonus for 2012 of $4 million, which was 114 percent of his target and approximately 16 percent lower than his cash incentive bonus
for 2011. In awarding his 2012 cash incentive bonus, our most important considerations were: (i)&nbsp;the low achievement of corporate performance goals, (ii)&nbsp;the above target achievement of management objectives, (iii)&nbsp;the overall target
achievement of regional performance goals, (iv)&nbsp;the record amount of production, (v)&nbsp;the increase in reserves excluding price-related adjustments, (vi)&nbsp;the critical realignment of the Kitimat project, and (vii)&nbsp;his exemplary
performance on other factors considered by the MD&amp;C Committee including the ones described above. </FONT></P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Other Named Executive Officers
</I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The individual performance component for the remaining named executive officers was based on the individual achievement of each executive,
as determined by the chairman and chief executive officer and recommended by him to the MD&amp;C Committee. A variety of qualitative and quantitative goals and performance results were taken into account, including leadership and management skills,
job responsibility, job complexity, and successful performance of an executive officer&#146;s business unit. There was no attempt to quantify, rank, or otherwise assign relative weights to these subjective factors. The chairman and chief executive
officer conducted an overall analysis of these factors and considered the totality of the information available to him. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">49 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">For Messrs. Plank, Eichler, and Lannie, the chairman and chief executive officer qualitatively assessed the
performance of their respective groups, considering 2012 results for various categories, including exploration, production, and drilling, and made recommendations to the MD&amp;C Committee as to the appropriate credit that should be given for
regional achievements. Mr.&nbsp;Chambers was evaluated by Mr.&nbsp;Plank and our chairman and chief executive officer who then made recommendations to the MD&amp;C Committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The named executive officers&#146; annual cash incentive bonus awards are set forth below and reflected in the Summary Compensation Table. </FONT></P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_23"></A>Long-Term Compensation Awards in 2012 </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In 2012, we granted Performance Shares, RSUs, and stock options to the named executive officers under our 2011 Omnibus Plan. The targeted grant date value
of long-term compensation for all named executive officers was allocated as follows: 35 percent Performance Shares, 35 percent RSUs, and 30 percent stock options. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In 2012, we awarded the following equity-based long-term incentive awards. Additional detail on these awards is provided in the &#147;Grants of Plan Based Awards Table.&#148; </FONT></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_24"></A>Historical Performance Share Results </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I><U>2010 TSR Program</U></I>: The performance period for the 2010 Performance Program began on January&nbsp;1, 2010, and ended on December&nbsp;31, 2012. The Stock Plan Committee certified the

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I><U>2008 Share Appreciation Program</U></I>: On May&nbsp;7, 2008, we established the 2008 Share
Appreciation Program (&#147;2008 SAP&#148;) under which, one-time conditional grants of approximately 2,773,000 shares of our common stock were made to substantially all of our full-time employees and eligible part-time employees. The conditional
grants were to vest only upon attainment of an initial price threshold of $162 per share of our common stock prior to year-end 2010 and a final price threshold of $216 per share prior to year-end 2012. The conditional grants issued under the 2008
SAP expired and were forfeited for all eligible employees because neither price threshold was achieved. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_25"></A>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION DECISION MAKING PROCESS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_26"></A>Role of the Board of Directors </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Compensation decision making for
executives is both a core Board responsibility and an effective tool for shaping our strategy and performance. The MD&amp;C Committee provides recommendations to the Board for the named executive officers&#146; (including the chairman and chief
executive officer&#146;s) base salary, annual cash incentive bonus, and long-term compensation multiples and components. The Board actively reviews the recommendations and approves them as recommended or with modifications. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_27"></A>Role of the Management Development and Compensation Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The MD&amp;C Committee, which met six times in 2012, plays a key role in the Board&#146;s compensation oversight and decision making. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The MD&amp;C Committee, on behalf of the Board of Directors, is responsible for reviewing and assessing the effectiveness of our compensation programs, in general, and our executive compensation programs
in particular. In performing these duties, the Committee reviews compensation programs and policies to avoid the incentivizing of excessive risk. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The MD&amp;C Committee&#146;s key responsibilities are: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">To review our goals and objectives, evaluate performance in light of such goals, and recommend the chairman and chief executive officer&#146;s
compensation to the Board for approval by the independent directors. This review is handled in independent sessions. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">To make recommendations to the Board concerning the base salary, incentive and equity-based compensation plans for executive officers other than the
chairman and chief executive officer. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Each of the MD&amp;C Committee&#146;s four members meets the independence requirements of the New York Stock Exchange and
NASDAQ listing standards. The MD&amp;C Committee&#146;s charter is available on our website. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_28"></A>Role of the Stock
Plan Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The principal purpose of the Stock Plan Committee is to assist the Board of Directors in the discharge of its
responsibilities relating to equity-based compensation of our employees. The Stock Plan Committee&#146;s key responsibilities are: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

statement. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

New York Stock Exchange and NASDAQ listing standards and is an outside director within the meaning of Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Internal Revenue Code. The Stock Plan Committee&#146;s charter is available on our website. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_29"></A>Role of the Compensation Consultant </B></FONT></P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Board and the MD&amp;C Committee have broad access to information to perform their compensation functions. The Board has authorized the MD&amp;C Committee to retain an independent compensation
consultant. In 2012, the MD&amp;C Committee retained the Consultant, Pearl Meyer&nbsp;&amp; Partners, to provide independent compensation advice and data to the MD&amp;C Committee and the Board.&nbsp;The Consultant performs an annual review of
executive total compensation relative to the market. In addition, the Consultant assesses the competitiveness of our compensation programs versus the practices of our compensation peers and reviews these programs for any potential risk. Except for
limited work for management in connection with the Consultant&#146;s published industry-specific surveys, for which the Consultant received <I>de minimis</I> compensation, the Consultant did not provide any services to Apache other than the
executive compensation-related services to the Board. After its review, the MD&amp;C Committee determined that no conflict of interest arose from the work performed by the Consultant. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Also, each year the MD&amp;C Committee reviews the independence of the Consultant to ensure that the Consultant is indeed independent. Among other things, this review includes a certification from the
Consultant in which the Committee is provided with written evidence of compliance with the Consultant&#146;s own rules regarding independence, which already include the newly adopted independence rules. This certification from the Consultant was
provided to the MD&amp;C Committee, and after its review, the MD&amp;C Committee determined that the Consultant was independent. </FONT></P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_30">
</A>Role of Management </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In addition to the use of the Consultant, the MD&amp;C Committee receives compensation recommendations and
evaluations of the executive group from the chairman and chief executive officer. The MD&amp;C Committee, along with each of the independent directors, is authorized by the Board to obtain information from and work directly with any employee in
fulfilling its responsibilities. Our executive vice president of human resources prepares information and materials for the chairman and chief executive officer and the MD&amp;C Committee for the exercise of their distinct, but interrelated,
compensation responsibilities. The MD&amp;C Committee also utilizes the data provided by the Consultant, including recommendations for the associated compensation values derived from their reports. The MD&amp;C Committee carefully considers the
chairman and chief executive officer&#146;s recommendations on these matters, reaches final determination, and reports these outcomes to the Board of Directors in the form of recommended actions. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">52 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_31"></A>TAX LEGISLATION RELATED TO COMPENSATION </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended, imposes a limit, with certain exceptions, on the amount that a publicly held
corporation may deduct in any tax year commencing on or after January&nbsp;1, 1994, for the compensation paid or accrued with respect to its chief executive officer and its three highest compensated officers for the year (other than the principal
executive officer or the principal financial officer). The MD&amp;C Committee continues to review our compensation plans based upon these regulations and, from time to time, determines what further actions or changes to our compensation plans, if
any, would be appropriate. It is the intention of the MD&amp;C Committee for us to receive shareholder approval for all future stock-based compensation plans so that they may qualify for the performance-based compensation exemption. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our 2005 Stock Option Plan, 2005 Share Appreciation Plan, 2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan (including the 2008 Share Appreciation Program and the
2010 and 2011 TSR Programs), and 2011 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan (including the 2012 and 2013 TSR Programs) were approved by our shareholders and grants made under such plans qualify as &#147;performance-based&#148; under the regulations. Our
existing annual cash incentive compensation plan, special achievement bonuses, and 2000 Stock Option Plan do not meet the requirements of the regulations, as the shareholder approvals necessary for exemption were not sought. However, these plans
operate similarly to prior or other existing plans and are designed to reward the contribution and performance of employees and to provide a meaningful incentive for achieving Apache&#146;s goals, which in turn enhances shareholder value. No further
grants can be made under the 2000 and 2005 Stock Option Plans, the 2005 Share Appreciation Plan, or the 2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan. While the MD&amp;C Committee cannot predict with certainty how our compensation policies may be further
affected by this limitation, it is anticipated that executive compensation paid or accrued pursuant to our compensation plans that have not met the requirements of the regulations will not result in any material loss of tax deductions in the
foreseeable future. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">On June&nbsp;24, 2011, the Internal Revenue Service issued proposed regulations clarifying that performance-based
compensation attributable to stock options and stock appreciation rights must specify the maximum number of shares with respect to which options or rights may be granted to each individual employee during a specified period in order to meet the
performance-based compensation exemption.&nbsp;These proposed regulations would apply to tax years ending on or after the date final regulations are issued.&nbsp;Our compensation plans currently include this provision. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Internal Revenue Code section 409A requires &#147;nonqualified deferred compensation plans&#148; to meet requirements in order to avoid acceleration of
the recipient&#146;s federal income taxation of the deferred compensation. The Internal Revenue Service issued final regulations in April 2007 regarding the application of Section&nbsp;409A, which were generally effective January&nbsp;1, 2009. Prior
to effectiveness, companies were expected to comply in &#147;good faith&#148; with the statute, taking note of the interim guidance issued by the Internal Revenue Service. We amended several of our benefit plans in order for them to be exempt from
Section&nbsp;409A, while we continue to provide benefits through several plans that remain subject to Section&nbsp;409A. The terms of these plans were amended before January&nbsp;1, 2009, as necessary, to meet the requirements of the final
regulations. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">53 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx470199_32"></A><A NAME="toc470199_24"></A>MANAGEMENT DEVELOPMENT AND
COMPENSATION COMMITTEE REPORT </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Management Development and Compensation Committee of the Board of Directors of Apache Corporation
reviewed and discussed with management the Compensation Discussion and Analysis set forth above, and based upon such review and discussion, recommended to the Board of Directors that the Compensation Discussion and Analysis be included in this proxy
statement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Members of the Management Development and</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Compensation Committee</FONT></P></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD HEIGHT="16"></TD>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">55 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>All Other Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Officers participate in two qualified retirement plans. The 401(k) Savings Plan provides a match up to the first six percent of base pay and incentive bonus. The Money Purchase Retirement Plan provides an
annual eight percent company contribution into the same investment choices as the 401(k) Savings Plan with the exception of Company stock. Additionally, officers can elect to participate in the Non-Qualified Retirement/Savings Plan to defer beyond
the limits in the 401(k) Savings Plan and continue Company contributions which exceed the limits in the qualified plans. The investment choices mirror those in the 401(k) Savings Plan and the Money Purchase Retirement Plan. The Deferred Delivery
Plan allows officers the ability to defer income in the form of deferred units from the vesting of restricted stock units under the Company&#146;s Executive Restricted Stock Plan, 2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan, and 2011 Omnibus Equity
Compensation Plan. The contributions into both non-qualified plans are reported in the Non-Qualified Deferred Compensation Table. The Company does not have a defined benefit plan for U.S. employees. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Apache provides U.S. employees with two times their base salary under group term life insurance. Executives receive the first $50,000 of coverage under
the same group term life insurance plan, and the remaining amount to bring them up to two times salary is provided in the form of whole life insurance policies. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Board requires G. Steven Farris to use the Company&#146;s aircraft for all air travel for security reasons and to facilitate efficient business travel, unless good business judgment requires
otherwise. Even though the Company considers these costs a necessary business expense rather than a perquisite for Mr.&nbsp;Farris, in line with SEC guidance, the following table includes the amounts attributable to each Named Executive
Officer&#146;s personal aircraft usage. Executives are not reimbursed for the taxes on the income attributable to the personal use of corporate aircraft. The methodology for the valuation of non-integral use of corporate aircraft for disclosure in
the Summary Compensation Table, in compliance with SEC guidance, calculates the incremental cost to the Company for personal use of the aircraft based on the cost of fuel and oil per hour of flight; trip-related inspections, repairs and maintenance;
crew travel expenses; on-board catering; trip-related flight planning services; landing, parking, and hanger fees; supplies; passenger ground transportation; and other variable costs. Additionally, the value of trips attributable to philanthropic
interests was included, even though they are seen as contributing to the goodwill of the Company. In addition, Standard Industry Fare Level (&#147;SIFL&#148;) tables, published by the Internal Revenue Service, are used to determine the amount of
compensation income that is imputed to the executive for tax purposes for personal use of corporate aircraft. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In addition to the benefits for
which all employees are eligible, the Company also covers the cost of an annual physical and pays 50 percent of health/fitness club membership dues and the full cost of enhanced long-term disability coverage for executive officers. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company provides various forms of compensation related to expatriate assignment that differ according to location and term of assignment, including:
foreign service premium, foreign assignment tax equalization, location pay, housing and utilities, home leave and travel, goods and services allowance, relocation expense, and tax return preparation. These items have been reflected in the following
table under Foreign Assignment Allowances for the amounts that pertain to Mr.&nbsp;Eichler. Mr.&nbsp;Eichler, as executive vice president &#151; Egypt, resided in Egypt during 2007, 2008, and January to June 2009. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">56 </FONT></P>

STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This amount for 2010 is for use of corporate aircraft related to Company-supported charitable interests. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:3px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(d)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This amount for 2012 includes $6,983 in tax credits related to foreign assignment and $750 for tax return preparation. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:3px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This amount for 2011 includes $21,911 for taxes related to foreign assignment and $750 for tax return preparation. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:3px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This amount for 2010 includes $272,277 for taxes related to foreign assignment and $250 for housing and utilities. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:3px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Executives assigned to foreign countries typically incur a change in their overall tax liability because most of the components of
assignment compensation that are provided in addition to base salary are taxable in the United States and in the foreign country. Therefore, the Company&#146;s expatriate assignment policy provides that it will be responsible for any additional
foreign or U.S. taxes due as a direct result of the international assignment and the executive remains financially responsible for the tax which he/she would have incurred if he/she had continued to live and work in the United States.&nbsp;Pursuant
to this policy, the Company withheld from Mr.&nbsp;Eichler&#146;s compensation an amount equivalent to the taxes that would have been due had he remained in the United States.&nbsp;Those funds were used to help pay taxes due in the United States and
in Egypt during the period of his foreign assignment.&nbsp;The Company paid taxes due in excess of Mr.&nbsp;Eichler&#146;s withholding that were incurred as a result of his foreign assignment. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">58 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc470199_26"></A>GRANTS OF PLAN BASED AWARDS TABLE </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The table below provides supplemental information relating to the Company&#146;s grants of stock options and restricted stock units during fiscal year
2012 to the Named Executive Officers. There were no stock appreciation rights granted during fiscal year 2012. Also included, in compliance with SEC rules on disclosure of executive compensation, is information relating to the estimated grant date
fair value of the grants. For stock options, the estimated fair value is based upon principles of the Black-Scholes option pricing model. The Black-Scholes model utilizes numerous arbitrary assumptions about financial variables such as interest
rates, stock price volatility and future dividend yield. Neither the values reflected in the table nor the assumptions utilized in arriving at the values should be considered indicative of future stock performance. </FONT></P>

Equity Compensation Plan, the Company established the 2012 Performance Program Specifications for all professional and management employees (excluding Egyptian nationals and non-exempt support staff and non-supervisory field staff) who are employed
on or before December&nbsp;31, 2011. These employees, including the executives named in the Summary Compensation Table, were granted the right to receive restricted stock units (&#147;RSUs&#148;), the number of which will be determined and for which
vesting will begin on December&nbsp;31, 2014 based on the Company&#146;s total shareholder return (&#147;TSR&#148;) as compared to a peer group of 18 companies. At the conclusion of the three-year performance period, which began on January&nbsp;1,
